  6  Defines the Liminf/Limsup of a function taking values in a conditionally complete lattice, with
  7  respect to an arbitrary filter.
  8  
  9  We define `f.Limsup` (`f.Liminf`) where `f` is a filter taking values in a conditionally complete
 10  lattice. `f.Limsup` is the smallest element `a` such that, eventually, `u ≤ a` (and vice versa for
 11  `f.Liminf`). To work with the Limsup along a function `u` use `(f.map u).Limsup`.
 12  
 13  Usually, one defines the Limsup as `Inf (Sup s)` where the Inf is taken over all sets in the filter.
 14  For instance, in ℕ along a function `u`, this is `Inf_n (Sup_{k ≥ n} u k)` (and the latter quantity
 15  decreases with `n`, so this is in fact a limit.). There is however a difficulty: it is well possible
 16  that `u` is not bounded on the whole space, only eventually (think of `Limsup (λx, 1/x)` on ℝ. Then
 17  there is no guarantee that the quantity above really decreases (the value of the `Sup` beforehand is
 18  not really well defined, as one can not use ∞), so that the Inf could be anything. So one can not
 19  use this `Inf Sup ...` definition in conditionally complete lattices, and one has to use the
 20  following less tractable definition.
 21  
 22  In conditionally complete lattices, the definition is only useful for filters which are eventually
 23  bounded above (otherwise, the Limsup would morally be +∞, which does not belong to the space) and
 24  which are frequently bounded below (otherwise, the Limsup would morally be -∞, which is not in the
 25  space either). We start with definitions of these concepts for arbitrary filters, before turning to
 26  the definitions of Limsup and Liminf.
 27  
 28  In complete lattices, however, it coincides with the `Inf Sup` definition.
 29  
 30  We use cLimsup in theorems in conditionally complete lattices, and Limsup for the corresponding
 31  theorems in complete lattices (usually with less assumptions).
 32  
 33  -/

 85  /-- `is_cobounded (≺) f` states that filter `f` is not tend to infinite w.r.t. `≺`. This is also
 86  called frequently bounded. Will be usually instantiated with `≤` or `≥`.
 87  
 88  There is a subtlety in this definition: we want `f.is_cobounded` to hold for any `f` in the case of
 89  complete lattices. This will be relevant to deduce theorems on complete lattices from their
 90  versions on conditionally complete lattices with additional assumptions. We have to be careful in
 91  the edge case of the trivial filter containing the empty set: the other natural definition
 92    `¬ ∀ a, ∀ᶠ n in f, a ≤ n`
 93  would not work as well in this case.
 94  -/
 95  def is_cobounded (r : α → α → Prop) (f : filter α) := ∃b, ∀a, (∀ᶠ x in f, r x a) → r b a
